04045nam a22005295i 9780887555800DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875558007 a10.1515/97808875558002doi  a(DE-B1597)664709  a(OCoLC)1148865576  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a947.7/10842231 aPatterson, Sean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMakhno and Memory :bAnarchist and Mennonite Narratives of Ukraine's Civil War, 1917–1921 /cSean Patterson. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tA Note on the Text -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tThrough Makhnovist Eyes -- tThrough Mennonite Eyes -- tThe Eichenfeld Massacre -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNestor Makhno has been called a revolutionary anarchist, a peasant rebel, the Ukrainian Robin Hood, a mass-murderer, a pogromist, and a devil. These epithets had their origins in the Russian Civil War (1917–1921), where the military forces of the peasant-anarchist Nestor Makhno and Mennonite colonists in southern Ukraine came into conflict. In autumn 1919, Makhnovist troops and local peasant sympathizers murdered more than 800 Mennonites in a series of large-scale massacres. The history of that conflict has been fraught with folklore, ideological battles and radically divergent cultural memories, in which fact and fiction often seamlessly blend, conjuring a multitude of Makhnos, each one shouting its message over the other. Drawing on theories of collective memory and narrative analysis, Makhno and Memory brings a vast array of Makhnovist and Mennonite sources into dialogue, including memoirs, histories, diaries, newspapers, and archival material. A diversity of perspectives are brought into relief through the personal reminiscences of Makhno and his anarchist sympathizers alongside Mennonite pacifists and advocates for armed self-defense. Through a meticulous analysis of the Makhnovist-Mennonite conflict and a micro-study of the Eichenfeld massacre of November 1919, Sean Patterson attempts to make sense of the competing cultural memories and presents new ways of thinking about Makhno and his movement. Makhno and Memory offers a convincing reframing of the Mennonite / Makhno relationship that will force a scholarly reassessment of this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnarchismzUkrainexHistoryy20th century. 0aCollective memoryzUkraine. 0aMennoniteszUkrainexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755580040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887555800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887555800/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles